Bank of England Discovers Google Data

-- B y   P a u l   K e d r o s k y
-- 
2011-06-14T11:23:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-14/bank-of-england-discovers-google-data.html
     June 14 (Bloomberg.com) -- A new paper shows that the  Bank
of England  has discovered the InterWeb, or at least Google
Insights for Search data. Here is the summary, but the entire
paper is worth reading.
Using internet search data as economic indicators  Data on the volume of online searches can be used as
indicators of economic activity.  This article examines the use
of these data for labour and housing markets in the  United
Kingdom .  These data provide some additional information relative
to existing surveys.  And with further development, internet
search data could become an important tool for economic analysis  Like you, I’m sure, I’m mostly worried that U.K. interest
rates are going to show a new correlation with “les paul,” “cool
math games,” and “euromillions.” Ah, well.  Click here  to see the story as it appeared on Bloomberg.com.
 